title: For Sale/Trade:  FS: Two Russian Mosin Nagant 91/30  Hex Receiver and MO Double Date Ex-sniper!
postcontent:
Two Russian Mosin Nagant 91/30 for sale.  Upcoming bills are forcing me to sell a few of my Mosins, these are rifles I was planning to keep and not something you will see too often! 

The first is a 1932 Izhevsk Hex Reciever Mosin.  This one has extensive "Blood Pitting" in the receiver area and is counter-bored with a dark bore.  Although I doubt the authenticity of so-called "blood pitting" the presence of damage prior to refurbishment indicates the rifle likely saw action making it an interesting piece!  Other than the pitting the stock is in great condition and this would make a great shooter! (see first two pictures) $140 (probably the cheapest hex Mosin you will see and a great rifle with actual history!)

Second is a VERY rare 91/30, 1943 Izhevsk MO double date marked AND an ex sniper!  This one would fill several holes in your collection and will make a solid investment.  Check the infamous Mosin rarity chart, MO double date is ranked 6/10 and ex-sniper is ranked 5/10, the combination of these features is VERY unusual (ex-snipers have filled holes from sniper scope mounts).  As any Izhevsk sniper should, this one has the proper lined-out scope serial number on the side of the action.  The stock has some gouges and isn't the best I have ever seen but to be honest for a rifle this rare the stock is almost an afterthought!  (see the last picture for receiver shot, photo was taken when I pulled the action) $210 (a steal for this rifle, only selling because I shouldn't have spent the money, going to school doesn't pay very well...)

Rifles are located in Tacoma, CPL/DL needed to complete transaction, I will need the DL for my C&R.

title: For Sale/Trade:  JUST FREE DIALOG ON AMMO PRICES
location: RALEIGH, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
HAD TO POST BASED ON ANOTHER REASONABLE POST YESTERDAY
Well this seems like a good place to share an opinion based on the sensible writings. I find it amusing and misguided to blame anyone for selling any ammo or write derogatoy comments about the prices when this is a perfectly fair thing to do. Let me share my story to explain. I starting with a 22 rifle when i was 14 and just shot targets for fun. Over the next 50 years i purchased another 22 pistol, a 38 spl and a 12 ga shotgun. Figured this was all i needed. About two years ago i decided to look into additional firearm purchases. I have worked hard and invested wisely so i had the cash to start a new hobby. I do everything legally and educated myself on gun safety, gun laws, and firearm and ammo spec's. Then i started to purchase firearms. I now shoot regularly at a shooting range. Last october i purchased a S&W M&P 15/22 and a Bersa 9mm from Gander Moutain. When i was purchasing the guns i asked for some 22lr and 9mm ammo. They offered me a bulk pack of 9mm for $243.00 and one brick of 22lr. They did not have anymore to sell. I went through the 22lr fairly quickly and decided to get some more. trips to Walmart, kmart, Gander Mountain and five local sporting goods stores turned up nothing. When i inquired about stock i was told that no one had an ideal when they would get any. On rare occasion i found one box per trip. So i started to look for other options, the internet. Today i have 20 firearms and know every available way to find ammo. I can tell you where to find it, what is the current best price, what shipping and handling will be, and even how and when seller will list product. I can predict how fast listed ammo will sell out and tricks sellers use to get the most out of each sale. I have not listed or sold any of the ammo i purchased on the intermet but i have sold to dealers at the local gun shows. I have purchased 22lr for $.05 to $.12 per round since October. I sold 11,000 22lr at the gun show for $1000.00, hardly gouging on my part. 15 minutes later the gun dealer was selling it all for $.20 per round. Avid shooter have to understand that there are a lot of new gun owners that need ammo that is in short supply. I purchased some of my ammo on gunbroker or armslist and was happy to pay the price to have the ammo. I find it amusing when i see the post that "got all the ammo at my local walmart today" and " i hope no one buys this overprice ammo". I tried Walmart at 6:30am without success. I also run a business that does not allow me to stand in line at Dicks or Gander Mountain. I work 11 hours per day unlike some of the individual who post such lame comments. If they wanted to help they could offer advise on how to find ammo instead of the usual response like "that's my secret" or "that's for me to know". Real helpful. Well the truth is that the ammo is only overpriced to the veteran gun owners. All the new gun owners figure that they will pay the going rate to have the product. Ammo is like gas or food. Sould i make hateful comments if you pay more for gas or food than i do? The sellers offer a service and a product that is needed. If not it would never sell. So i have no problem with anyone buying and reselling to make a profit. That is a fundamental right in our country. Not something we pick or chose based on what my affect us individually. I will gladly offer every secret, trick or source to anyone that needs to buy ammo. Let's see what kind of response i get to this post. I now have every firearm i want and enough ammo to shoot comfortably for 12 months. Please, let's have a fair and logical discussion on this topic. Thanks for reading the rant of an old guy. OLD GUYS RULE.
